<title type="html"><![CDATA[11/8 (Thu.) Top 50 Travel APPs/ Top 50 Most Livable Cities (Host: Morris)]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://www.royalclub.tw/bbs3/viewtopic.php?t=223&amp;p=237#p237"><![CDATA[
<span style="font-weight: bold">Session I: Top 50 Travel APPs</span><br /> <br />Nobody wants to show up at a luxury beachfront resort only to realize it’s a roach-motel from hell, nor does anyone want to choose the only seat on the plane that doesn’t recline. Doing ample research before any trip is a great way to ensure you spend more time relaxing and less time stressing! These Top Travel Research Apps will satisfy your inner Type-A and help you get the best bang for your buck.<br /><br />Please read the following link for more detail:<br /><a href="https://www.traveloffpath.com/top-50-travel-apps-in-2018/" class="postlink">https://www.traveloffpath.com/top-50-travel-apps-in-2018/</a><br /><br /><span style="font-weight: bold">I list the top 20 for discussion as follows:</span><br />1. TripAdvisor<br />2. Yelp<br />3. Google Maps<br />4. SeatGuru<br />5. GateGuru<br />6. Elk Currency Converter<br />7. Hotels Combined<br />8. AirBnB<br />9. Trivago<br />10. Last Minute Travel<br />11. Hotel Quickly<br />12. Booking<br />13. Google Flights<br />14. Momondo<br />15. Hopper<br />16. SkyScanner<br />17. Duolingo<br />18. Tiny Cards<br />19. World Maps<br />20. Calm<br />  <br /><span style="font-weight: bold">Questions:</span><br />1.Do you prefer traveling by joining a package tour or by backpacking? Why?<br />2.Among the top 20 Apps, how many of them have you used?  Which of them are the most useful to you? Why?<br />3.To use travel apps, being on-line is necessary, so how do you usually make sure that you can be on-line when you travel abroad?  Any tips?<br />4.Besides the top 20 apps, what other apps or tools you know are also helpful? <br />           <br /><span style="font-weight: bold">Session II: Top 50 Most Livable Cities</span><br /><br />When it comes to choosing a place to live, there are several factors to consider — climate, transportation options, and crime rates, to name a few. Although it's hard to find a perfect match, a few select cities have the perfect combination of factors that make them the most livable in the world.<br /><br />The Economist Intelligence Unit released its annual Global Liveability Index, and for the first time in eight years, Melbourne, Australia, did not take the top spot on the list. <br /><br />The Economist ranked 140 major cities by averaging the results of five metrics:<br /><br />1.<span style="font-weight: bold">Stability</span>, including the prevalence of petty and violent crime, the threat of terror, and the threat of military conflict.<br /><br />2.<span style="font-weight: bold">Healthcare</span>, including the availability and quality of healthcare, both public and private<br /><br />3.<span style="font-weight: bold">Culture and environment</span>, including climate, level of corruption, level of censorship, and sporting availability<br /><br />4.<span style="font-weight: bold">Education</span>, including the availability and quality of private education<br /><br />5.<span style="font-weight: bold">Infrastructure</span>, including the quality of road networks and public transport, the availability of good quality housing, the quality of telecommunications, and the quality of water and energy provisions<br /><br />Please read the following link for more detail:<br /><a href="https://www.businessinsider.com/most-livable-cities-in-the-world-2018-8" class="postlink">https://www.businessinsider.com/most-livable-cities-in-the-world-2018-8</a><br /><br /><span style="font-weight: bold">I list the top 20 for discussion as follows::</span><br />1. Vienna<br />2. Melbourne<br />3. Osaka<br />4. Calgary<br />5. Sydney<br />6. Vancouver<br />7. Tokyo<br />8. Toronto<br />9. Copenhagen<br />10. Adelaide<br />11. Zurich<br />12. Auckland<br />13. Frankfurt<br />14. Geneva<br />15. Perth<br />16. Helsinki<br />17. Amsterdam<br />18. Hamburg<br />19. Montreal<br />20. Paris<br /> <br /><span style="font-weight: bold">Questions:</span><br />1.How many times have you traveled abroad? How many cities have you been to? Which one do you like the best? Why?<br />2.Among the top 20 cities, how many of them have you been to? Which of them do you like the best? Why? <br />3.The Economist adopts five factors, including Stability, healthcare, culture and environment, education, and infrastructure, to rank the cities.  Which factor is the most important one for you when considering living in or traveling to a city? What other factors you think are also crucial?  <br />4.If you can choose one city to live after you retire, which city do you prefer? Why? <br /><br /><span style="font-weight: bold">Agenda:</span><br />7:00-7:25 Greetings and free talk<br />7:25-7:30 Opening remarks/ Newcomers self-introduction/ Grouping<br />(Session I)<br />7:30 ~ 8:10pm discussion session (40 mins)<br />8:10 ~ 8:25pm summarization (15 mins)<br />8:25 ~ 8:30pm Regrouping<br />(Session II)<br />8:30 ~9:10pm discussion session (40 mins)<br />9:10 ~9:25pm summarization (15 mins)<br />9:25 ~9:30pm Concluding remarks/feedback from newcomers<br /><br /><span style="font-weight: bold">The meeting place of Thursday:</span><br />丹堤咖啡寶慶店：台北市延平南路107號2F (上樓右邊第一區塊)<br />捷運資訊： 近台北捷運–西門站 (4號出口步行約2分鐘，康是美隔壁)<br />丹堤低消: NT$80元<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://www.royalclub.tw/bbs3/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=827">Jason Tang</a> — Fri Nov 02, 2018 1:17 pm</p><hr />
